COMPENSATION TO THOS. SW'EETMAN.

Mr. DAWSON asked. 1. Has the question of compensation to Mr. Sweetman, of Fer- moy, for damages done to lot 26 in the seventh concesssion of Bedford. been under the consideration of the Council ? 2. What action has been taken ? 3. Has he receiv- ed compensation yet ‘3 4. If so, when was he paid. and how much ? 5. If not yet paid, why not '3

«Mr. HAGGART. The question of com- pensation [to Mr. Thomas Sweetman for damages to lot 26, in concession No. 27, Bed- ford, has been under consideration. It is proposed to ask Parliament to vote 52m in the Supplementary Estimates for 1893-94 in discharge of the claim. He has not yet received any compensation. It was not paid because he refused to accept the sum of $220 when offered him, and afterwards when he intimated his readiness to accept. there was no appropriation available.

EXPORTATION OF DIVE CATTLE.

Mr. MULOCK asked, What was the total number and value of live cattle exported to the United Kingdom in the calendar years 1890, 1891, 1892, and 1893 ‘3

Mr. WALLACE. In 1890 there were 104,133 live cattle exported to the United Kingdom, of the value of $8,114,145 ; in 1891, 99,967, of the value of $7,381,284; in 1892, 93,206, of the value of $6,920,748; in 1893, $572, of the value of $6,799,638, or a total during the four years of 386,878, of the value of $29,215,815.

AMERICA-N SWIN E.

Mr. FEATHERSTON asked. Has the Gov- ernment issued an order admitting Ameri- can swine in bond for slaughter purposes ? If so, have they to comply with quarantine regulations as now in force when imported for breeding purposes ‘2

Mr. FOSTER. Swine may be imported for slaughter, , in bond. under the provisions of an Order in Council, passed in .1880, and

39g ~

an Order passed in 1883, being chapter 9 of the Consolidated Orders in Council of Canada. Swine imported for slaughter in bond have not to comply with the quaran- tine regulations in force relating to animals for breeding purposes, but. the regulations are special. having for their object to secure complete isolation until they enter the shanghter-houses, from which they are not allowed to be removed alive. Such slaugh- tor-houses are required to be distinct from those in which Canadian swine are slaught- ered.
